Its an interesting question, what it means when we simultaneously drive animals to extinction in the wild yet in a sense provide a new niche which they thrive in. Theres stuff like urban foxes, coyotes and racoons, who now live a very different lifestyle from their wilder cousins. Lots of city birds as well, who now rely on those cities because their natural habitats are gone. And ofcourse theres domesticated animals like dogs, cats, sheep etc who we keep both for work and pleasure, who dont really have a wild habitat they are suited for anymore.

At least in this case, there is an alternative. Far too many species just lose their habitat and can neither adapt nor end up with a new one.

evolution is such a misleading term tho, even scientifically.

An organism doesn't simply go " Imma develop the ability to breathe water real quick"

Mutation and convergent evolution makes that happen ... meaning, it's much more likely that there were many types of axolotl, that developed different mutations but still were able to breed with each other.

Talking about species evolving, asnif they were a monolith, it's just wrong and not how actual evolution happens.

That makes it confusing for people that have yet to accept evolution as a scientific fact, as they can rightfully go " how can a dog develop wings?"

... because it can't! The fictional dog that eventually develops wings is either an ancestor of the dog evolutionaty tree that has the potential to devolop those characteristics, or alternatively an incredibly RARE mutation ... but that has nothing to do with "adapting to the environment" xD ... that is only a consequence of that completely random mutation being advantagious or not in the animal's environment.
